","–Female":"Deceased","1153–Male":"1153–Deceased","1165–1209":"1165–1209","1185–1250":"1185–1250","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1090":"1090","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1209":"1209","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Drakenage, England":"England","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitzwilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Humphrey Fitzwilliam de Drakenage was born in 1130, in Musbury, Devon, England as the son of William Fitz Harold de Drakenage Drake. He had at least 3 sons with Maud Fitz Hugh d'Abrincis. He died in 1195, in Devon, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1130–1195":"1130–1195","–Female":"Surnud","1153–Male":"1153–Surnud","1165–1209":"1165–1209","1185–1250":"1185–1250","1090–1166":"1090–1166","1090":"1090","1166":"1166","1165":"1165","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1209":"1209","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Drakenage, England":"England","Musbury, Devon, England":"Musbury, Devon, England","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1130–1